# Section 2 — Project Objectives & Scope

---

# 2.1 Background

The rapid advancement of Large Language Models (LLMs) has significantly improved conversational AI. Modern models such as Gemini, GPT, Claude, and others possess strong reasoning capabilities and can answer a wide range of general knowledge questions.

However, a standalone LLM has important limitations:

- It cannot reliably access real-time information.
- It cannot execute external actions.
- It cannot interact with enterprise systems.
- It cannot retrieve organization-specific knowledge unless explicitly connected to external tools.
- It cannot generate dynamic outputs such as reports or interact with third-party services on its own.

These limitations become increasingly important when building production-grade AI applications.

The objective of this project was to explore how these limitations can be overcome using the **Google Agent Development Kit (Google ADK)** together with the **Model Context Protocol (MCP)**.

Rather than building another chatbot, this project focuses on building an **AI agent** capable of reasoning, selecting specialized tools, invoking external services, and combining their outputs into a coherent response.

---

# 2.2 Problem Statement

Students planning to study abroad often need information from multiple independent sources.

A typical student may ask:

> *"I want to pursue Artificial Intelligence in Germany. Which universities should I consider? What scholarships are available? What is the cost of living? What visa requirements apply? What is the weather like? Which attractions are nearby?"*

Answering this single question requires information from several domains:

- University discovery
- Program comparison
- Scholarships
- Visa regulations
- Cost of living
- Geographic information
- Weather
- Nearby attractions

Traditionally, a student must visit multiple websites to gather this information.

The goal of this project is to demonstrate that a single AI agent can orchestrate multiple specialized tools to provide a unified response.

---

# 2.3 Why Google ADK?

Google ADK provides an orchestration framework that separates:

- **Reasoning** (performed by the LLM)
- **Execution** (performed by external tools)

This architectural separation enables the language model to determine **what** needs to be done while allowing specialized systems to perform **how** it is done.

Instead of embedding every capability inside the language model, ADK allows capabilities to be attached as reusable tools.

This project uses ADK to validate this design philosophy in a practical application.

---

# 2.4 Why MCP (Model Context Protocol)?

The Model Context Protocol (MCP) is an open protocol that standardizes communication between AI models and external tools.

Rather than writing custom integrations for every service, MCP defines a consistent interface through which the AI agent can:

- Discover available tools
- Invoke tool functions
- Exchange structured inputs and outputs
- Combine results from multiple services

This standardization significantly simplifies integration and improves portability.

The project intentionally uses both:

- Remote MCP servers
- Local MCP servers

to demonstrate different deployment models.

---

# 2.5 Why This Use Case?

The Study Abroad domain was selected because it naturally requires information from multiple independent systems.

A realistic recommendation involves:

- Web search for universities
- Scholarship databases
- Visa information
- Cost-of-living estimates
- Geographic information
- Weather services
- Report generation

This makes it an ideal scenario to evaluate multi-tool orchestration.

The application therefore serves as an excellent proof of concept for enterprise AI workflows that require information aggregation from diverse sources.

